{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17623831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17623831"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:13:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16876"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16876","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16876"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0,0.91,0,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9566"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67432"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9566","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9566"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16876"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52884"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"9861"},{"type":"tags","id":"9862"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22587"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22594"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/67432"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring moderate exercise, cardiac output increases to meet the increased oxygen demands of skeletal muscle.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism for increased cardiac output during moderate exercise?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Increased heart rate with decreased stroke volume","Decreased heart rate with increased stroke volume","Increased heart rate and stroke volume","Decreased peripheral resistance with constant heart rate","Increased blood pressure with constant stroke volume"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECardiac output (CO) = Heart Rate (HR) x Stroke volume (SV) \u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDuring exercise, \u003Cstrong\u003Eincreased heart rate and stroke volume\u003C/strong\u003E work together to \u003Cstrong\u003Eelevate cardiac output. \u003C/strong\u003EHeart rate increases due to sympathetic stimulation and parasympathetic withdrawal. Stroke volume increases through enhanced venous return from skeletal muscle pump action and stronger myocardial contractility.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased heart rate with decreased stroke volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Stroke volume actually increases during exercise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased heart rate with increased stroke volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Heart rate increases rather than decreases during exercise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased blood pressure with constant stroke volume\u003C/strong\u003E - Stroke volume changes significantly during exercise\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDecreased peripheral resistance with constant heart rate\u003C/strong\u003E - While peripheral resistance does decrease, heart rate increases substantially\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe combination of increased heart rate and stroke volume allows cardiac output to increase from approximately 5 L/min at rest to 20-25 L/min during maximal exercise in untrained individuals.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["During exercise, cardiac output increases primarily through increases in both heart rate and stroke volume.","Stroke volume increases during exercise due to enhanced venous return and stronger myocardial contractility."],"references":["Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52884"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16876"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52884","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52884"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-05T14:10:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-05T14:11:37+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9566"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"67432"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api